{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471936"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:53:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.21,0.48,0.05,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/881"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"363"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1675"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44036"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/45354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-day-old male infant presents to hospital with his parents with failure to pass meconium, abdominal distension, and bile-stained vomiting. He was born at term via normal vaginal delivery, which was uncomplicated. He has no significant medical history. On examination, he appears well with a distended abdomen. His vital signs are within normal limits. A plain abdominal X-ray shows gaseous distension with several air-fluid levels throughout the gut.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to provide the definitive diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contrast enema","Abdominal ultrasound","Rectal suction biopsy","CT enteroclysis","Anal manometry"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal X-ray identifying multiple air-fluid levels throughout the gut is suggestive of distal obstruction in a neonate and should prompt clinical suspicion of \u003Cstrong\u003EHirschsprung disease\u003C/strong\u003E. A male infant with failure to pass meconium, bilious vomiting, and progressive abdominal distention is the characteristic clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHirschsprung disease, caused by failure of colonic ganglion cell migration during gestation, results in segmental failure of the distal colon to relax, causing functional colonic obstruction. It is one of the most common causes of neonatal colonic obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eanal manometry\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast enema\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful as diagnostic screens, definitive diagnosis relies on histopathological confirmation. \u003Cstrong\u003ERectal suction biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common method of obtaining tissue samples for histology. Confirmatory histological features include a complete absence of ganglionic nerve cells with submucosal nerve hypertrophy and absent calretinin immunoreactive mucosal innervation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful in diagnosing Hirschsprung disease. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT enteroclysis\u003C/strong\u003E involves intubation of the small bowel and infusion of contrast material directly into the lumen. It is not indicated in neonates with suspected Hirschsprung disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Clinical suspicion of Hirschsprung disease requires a rectal suction biopsy to confirm the diagnosis."],"references":["Carlson Merrow A, Hariharan S. Imaging in Pediatrics. Elsevier; 2018.","Ambartsumyan L, Smith C, Kapur R. Diagnosis of Hirschsprung Disease. Pediatric and Developmental Pathology. 2019;23(1):8-22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-13T20:46:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-22T20:52:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"881"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"45354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduati